2":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","29 June 1561":"29 June 1561","1549":"1549","about 1560":"about 1560","Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","Saint John the Baptist Church, Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","St Botolph's Church, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"St Botolph's Church, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spooner","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from an unrecorded Middle English <i>sponer</i>, of uncertain meaning. It appears to be a derivative of Middle English <i>spon</i> ‘chip of wood, shingle, spoon’, and could denote either someone who made or fitted wooden roofing shingles or who made and sold spoons as eating implements, typically of wood or horn."],"variants":[{"name":"Spoon","meanings":["Dutch: from Dutch <i>spoon</i>, a variant of <i>poon</i> ‘gurnard (a species of marine fish with a large spiny head)’.","Possibly also English: metonymic occupational name either for a maker of roofing shingles or spoons, from Old English <i>spōn</i> ‘chip, splinter’ (see   Spooner  ).","Americanized form of German   Spohn   (see   Spahn  )."]}]},{"name":"Mariam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Aramaic alternative form of the Hebrew name   Miriam  , which now has currency in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":9,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705202,"age":18,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705206,"age":31,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705207,"age":45,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705212,"age":80,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1705213,"age":102,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"Mariam Spooner was born in 1540, in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England. She married Christopher Dising about 1560. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Denham, Suffolk, England, and was buried in Denham, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1540–":"1540–Surnud","1536–1590":"1536–1590","1561–1600":"1561–1600","1540–Female":"1540–Surnud","8 May 1626":"8. mai 1626","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1558":"1558","1536":"1536","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","29 June 1561":"29. juuni 1561","1549":"1549","about 1560":"umbes 1560","Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","Saint John the Baptist Church, Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","St Botolph's Church, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"St Botolph's Church, Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1540–":"1540–Kuollut","1536–1590":"1536–1590","1561–1600":"1561–1600","1540–Female":"1540–Kuollut","8 May 1626":"8. toukokuuta 1626","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1558":"1558","1536":"1536","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","29 June 1561":"29. kesäkuuta 1561","1549":"1549","about 1560":"noin 1560","Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","Saint John the Baptist Church, Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, Engl